It is generally recognized that energetic X-ray photons emitted by active galaxies and/or X-ray binaries may have significantly altered the thermal and ionization balance of the early neutral IGM. Since only highly energetic photons result in more than one ionization, this process is only important for radiation emitted by AGNs and X-ray binaries, while stars hardly emit any photons that are able to ionize hydrogen more than once. Unlike stellar UV photons, X-ray photons can easily escape from their host galaxies, quickly establish a homogeneous X-ray background, make the low-density IGM warm and weakly ionized prior to the epoch of reionization breakthrough, set an entropy floor, reduce gas clumping, and promote gas-phase H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
